text: Hi everyone, question(s) my company is a 2-3 year old startup and right now we have a LOT of content that focuses on solving the various use cases that our product serves. Bc we’re still new, we’re trying to get content out in front of the personas we’ve developed versus a specific market size or vertical/industry. So we’re creating content for Salesforce admins around helping people drive digital adoption. But not necessarily creating content that is unique for SMBs who are struggling with Salesforce adoption. I’m a month in to the company and created our Q2 content plan but the CEO wants to see more around what markets we’re going after and how our content addresses this. My team says we still need to focus on serving the industries/personas not crafting specialized messaging for market size bc we’re not there yet and still trying to build brand awareness, focus advertising dollars on content that solves for those outcomes. Any ideas how I can position this back to the CEO or explain it better? I’m trying to analyze all the content we have now to be able to identify gaps but none of it is really for a biz size specifcally.

text: Hi everyone, our company held a webinar with a couple of partners last week and one of the partners has written a recap on their blog. They would like us to also host the blog (along with the other participating partner) on our site. I'm not sure what the best way to do this for SEO is, can anyone give guidance?

elements.text: Hi everyone, our company held a webinar with a couple of partners last week and one of the partners has written a recap on their blog. They would like us to also host the blog (along with the other participating partner) on our site. I'm not sure what the best way to do this for SEO is, can anyone give guidance?

text:
Did your company host the webinar? I believe whichever company did the heavy lifting should "own" the content and write the original recap.

Regarding the SEO aspect of it, you can link to the recap from your blog, but it won't help your SEO at all since you're linking to the original (and more in-depth) post. They have the canonical URL, so you won't see any search traffic at all if you just rehost.

If you write your own recap, you can backlink to the recap while still adding in your company's unique content to give the post a chance at ranking
